Abstract

This dissertation argues that AI-to-AI communication will evolve from a technical by-product of software engineering into a decisive institutional layer of the knowledge economy. Its central claim is that effective artificial agents do not rely solely on powerful statistical models, but on three integrated components: skills as encapsulated operational capabilities, concepts as shared semantic schemas, and dialects as local conventions for expression, compression, prioritization, and verification. When these elements remain implicit, multi-agent systems exhibit semantic drift, operational ambiguity, weak auditability, and incentive misalignment. When they are formalized as governance objects, agent cooperation becomes more interpretable, composable, and controllable.

The dissertation proposes a seven-layer theoretical framework for agent communication: perception, representation, intention, negotiation, execution, verification, and memory. Across these layers, the work shows that interaction quality depends less on superficial fluency and more on the preservation of reference, context, commitment, and acceptance criteria. It also offers a functional taxonomy of AI-to-AI skills, a semantic model for shared concepts, and a typology of machine dialects oriented toward computational cost, safety, domain specialization, and reliability. The broader conclusion is that the future of applied artificial intelligence depends less on how intelligent an isolated model is, and more on how well communities of agents coordinate knowledge, responsibility, and action under institutional constraints.

Keywords: AI-to-AI; artificial agents; semantic protocols; machine dialects; multi-agent systems; algorithmic governance; cognitive interoperability.

